SENATE JOINT RESOLUTION 1128
By Hensley
A RESOLUTION to honor and recognize Xavier Wesley Shook,
2026 Top Ten Senior at Lewis County High
School.
WHEREAS, it is fitting that the members of this General Assembly should pause to pay
tribute to those students who, through their natural talents and unflagging commitment to
academic excellence, have distinguished themselves in the classroom; and
WHEREAS, Xavier Wesley Shook is one such exceptional student, who was recently
named a Top Ten Senior of the 2026 graduating class at Lewis County High School; and
WHEREAS, through diligent study, steady composure during examinations, and
steadfast commitment of time and talent, Mr. Shook has achieved outstanding academic
success and joined the ranks of the best and brightest students in Tennessee and our country;
and
WHEREAS, in his remarkable high school career, Xavier Shook has earned an
exemplary grade point average while participating in numerous extracurricular activities,
including band and Boys State; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Shook's display of intellectual aptitude and ambition surely bodes well
for his future success as a student at Middle Tennessee State University, where he plans to
study psychology; and
WHEREAS, Xavier Shook's noteworthy achievement is a tremendous source of pride for
his parents, Brian Shook and Crystal Shook, his school, and his community; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Shook's dedication to excellence is clearly deserving of the respect,
admiration, and commendation of the members of this General Assembly; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE SENATE OF THE ONE HUNDRED FOURTEENTH
GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE HOUSE OF
SJR1128
017664
- 1 -

REPRESENTATIVES CONCURRING, that we hereby commend and honor Xavier Wesley
Shook on being named a 2026 Lewis County High School Top Ten Senior, salute his
impressive academic achievement, and extend to him our best wishes for a happy, successful
future.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
